File: The Africa Continental Free Trade Agreement will see all but one of Africa’s 55 countries cutting cross-border tariffs. AFP/Issouf Sanogo JOHANNESBURG - A free-trade pact between African countries came into effect on Friday. The Africa Continental Free Trade Agreement will see all but one of Africa’s 55 countries cutting cross-border tariffs. The bloc has a potential market of 1.2 billion people and a combined gross domestic product of $2.5-trillion. READ: How a post-COVID-19 revival could kickstart Africa's free trade area Intra-Africa trade could be boosted from its current level of 15 percent to 22 percent under the agreement. The pact seeks to eliminate tariffs on most goods, facilitate the movement of capital and people, and promote investment. But poor infrastructure and corruption have been cited as some of the biggest hurdles.